<dl id="n54126b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n54" href="#n54126b">N54 (VI.B.45)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n54all.htm#n54126b"> 126(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> a regale <small>Green</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n54126b"><li>FW 184.24 </li><li><a href="../../flex/g/lexg.htm#n54126b">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/g/l39g.htm#n54126b">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n54126b">MS BL 47476a-254</ms> </li><li>JJA 49:527 <a name="gd11" href="../../FF/fdra/gda.htm#gd11">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/g/gd11.htm#n54126b">Draft: I.7&sect;1.11</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">The Dean then asked me, &lsquo;if I was a Queen, what I should choose to have after dinner?&rsquo; I answered, &lsquo;His conversation;&rsquo; &lsquo;Pooh!&rsquo; says he, &lsquo;I mean what <mark>regale</mark>?&rsquo; &lsquo;A dish of coffee, Sir;&rsquo; &lsquo;Why then I will so far make you as happy as a Queen&mdash;you shall have some in perfection; for when I was Chaplain to the Earl of <i>Berkley</i>, who was in the Government here, I was so poor, I was obliged to keep a coffee-house, and all the nobility resorted to it to talk treason.&rsquo; I could not help smiling at this oddity, but I really had such an awe on me, that I could not venture to ask him, as I longed to do, what it meant? <small> Letitia Pilkington, <a name="MMLP" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#MMLP"><cite title="source">Memoirs</cite></a> (1928) 52</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Regale: repast, feast. </mm> </dd></dl>
